misconceptions.student_thought_process: The student believes that the standard algorithm for a right array shift (storing the last element, conceptually shifting all other elements one position to the right starting from the end, and then placing the stored element at the beginning) correctly implements the requested array right shift operation.
misconceptions.conceptual_gap: There is no conceptual gap related to array index manipulation or operation order. The student has correctly implemented the array right shift algorithm: 1. Store the last element (y[n-1]). 2. Iterate backward from the penultimate index (n-1) down to 1, copying the element at i-1 to i (y[i]=y[i-1]). 3. Place the stored element in the first position (y[0]).
misconceptions.error_manifestation: The student code produces the correct output for the problem statement and sample run.
